<p>The photographer's MacBook Pro was returned with fully functional display including all XDR features (local dimming, HDR, high brightness). Six months later (February 2025), display continues working perfectly.</p>
</section>

<section class="case-lessons">
<h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Complete display replacement isn't always necessary:</strong> Many <a href="/macbook-screen-issues/">display failures</a> are component-level issues, not panel failures.</li>
  <li><strong>Mini-LED displays have complex backlight systems:</strong> Multiple failure points exist beyond just the panel.</li>
  <li><strong>External monitor test is crucial:</strong> Quickly isolates whether the problem is display or logic board.</li>
  <li><strong>AppleCare may have covered this:</strong> At 14 months, this was just out of standard warranty but would have been covered by AppleCare+.</li>
</ul>
</section>

